<tr>
<td align="center"colspan="2" valign="top" height=50><br><div><font size="+5" color=#990000>
Repetition of the Indirect Object Pronoun</font><hr color=#990000></div></td>
</tr>


<!-- this is the content table -->


<tr><td><div>
The indirect object pronoun is sometimes <strong>repeated for emphasis or 
to clarify</strong> who you are talking about.  Note that "le" and "les" have
several meanings:<br><br>

<table align="center" cellpadding=0 width="850" bgcolor="#F6BA7C">
<tr>
<td colspan=4 align="center"><div><font color="#3915B4"><strong>The multiple meanings of "le" and "les"</strong></font></div></td></tr>
<tr>
<td width="10%"><div><font color="#3915B4"><strong>le:</strong></font></div></td>
<td width="30%"><div><font size="4"> <strong>you</strong> formal singular: usted</font></div></td>
<td width="30%"><div><font size="4"> <strong>him</strong>: &eacute;l </font></div></td>
<td width="30%"><div><font size="4"> <strong>her</strong>: ella</font></div></td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td><div><font color="#3915B4"><strong>les:</strong></font></div></td>
<td><div><font size="4"> <strong>you</strong> formal plural: ustedes</font></div></td>
<td><div><font size="4"> <strong>them</strong> masculine: ellos</font></div></td>
<td><div><font size="4"> <strong>them</strong> feminine: ellas</font></div></td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>
Because of the multiple meaning of "le" and "les" you may need to clarify what you mean.  In other 
cases, you may want to emphasize who receives the action.  Check out these examples:<br>
<br>


<table align="center" cellpadding=5  width="850">
<tr bgcolor="#E0F0F5">
<td><div>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>me</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a m&iacute;</strong></font>.<br>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>te</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a ti</strong></font>.<br>
</div></td>
<td><div>< emphasis<br> < emphasis
</div></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor=#BBE1C6>
<td><div>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>le</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a usted</strong></font>.<br>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>le</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a &eacute;l</strong></font>.<br>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>le</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a ella</strong></font>.<br>
</div></td>
<td><div>< clarification<br>< clarification<br>< clarification
</div></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#E0F0F5">
<td><div>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>nos</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a nosotros</strong></font>.<br>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>os</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a vosotros</strong></font>.<br>
</div></td>
<td><div>< emphasis<br> < emphasis
</div></td>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor=#BBE1C6>
<td><div>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>les</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a ustedes</strong></font>.<br>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>les</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a ellos</strong></font>.<br>
Teresa <font color="#3915B4"><strong>les</strong></font> vende su libro <font color="#3915B4"><strong>a ellas</strong></font>.<br>
</div></td>
<td><div>< clarification<br>< clarification<br>< clarification
</div></td>
</tr>

</table><br>
The pronouns used to emphasize or clarify in these examples are called 
<font color="#3915B4"><strong>"prepositional pronouns"</strong></font> because 
they follow prepositions ("a" in the example).

<br>


</div></td></tr>
